  (text "*External Coil circuitry" 
    (exclude_from_sim no) 
    (at 266.446 115.57 0) 
    (effects 
      (font 
        (size 1.27 1.27))) 
    (uuid "4270a8af-b1c0-4ead-9972-df34438908cb")) 
  (text "*External Battery \n Circuitry\n" 
    (exclude_from_sim no) 
    (at 260.858 16.51 0) 
    (effects 
      (font 
        (size 1.27 1.27)) 
      (justify left)) 
    (uuid "4e34a75f-5642-4484-97d1-edbf25043987")) 
  (text "1. Here is the USB-C input where power can be supplied to charge the battery from the Vbus pin (5V)\nand program the ESP32-WROOM-E via the D+/- pins. The 5.1k ohm resistors R3 and R4 are used to let the \ncomputer (if we're using it to charge) know that the vape is recieving power and information. The \nResistors also establish the same power recieving dynamic with a power outlet.\n2. This is the Battery Charging module led by the TP4056. The power comes in from the USB-C and gets\ndelivered safely to the battery from the TP4056. The R2 resistor configures the TP4056 to the 1A charging\nmode. I also included an LED connection to the charge pin on the TP4056 in case we wanted to have some LED\noutput to let the user know the vape is fully charged. \n3. This is the battery protection circuit, protecting the battery from drawing too much current, over charging, \nas well as disconnecting the battery when the voltage drops to 3V to avoid damaging the battery when it tries to\ndischarge at a significantly low battery level.\n4. This is the 3.7V to 3.3V LDO component. This steps down the battery voltage from 3.7V to 3.3V via the AP2112K\nLDO.\n5. This is the programming component of the circuit. The CH340C is a USB to UART programmer, and when paired with\nBC817 transistors, the ESP32 can be programmed via a USB-C interface with the Arduino IDE.\n6. The ESP32 component. This is connected to the 3.3V output from the AP2112K, CH340C UART pins, and peripherals\nconnected to the ESP32 for capturing data regarding the users habits and container volume remaining.\n7. This is the pressure sensor input to the ESP32. For this schematics purpose, I modelled it as just a button,\nbut in actuality we plan on using a pressure sensor that we can't acutally find a schematic for. So for conceptual\nunderstanding, the button is how the ESP32 will know when the user is trying to hit the vape.\n8. This is the coil driver component. The AO3400A NMOS is paired with input resistors to the gate and a pull down \nresistor. The pull down resistor will ensure that the coil isn't powered when the ESP32 is being programmed or booted\nas pins can act weird sometimes. The series resistor to the gate will help smooth out the capacitance of the gate by \nslowing down the current transported to the gate while PWM is switching on and off the gate.\n" 
    (exclude_from_sim no) 
    (at 13.97 167.64 0) 
    (effects 
      (font 
        (size 1.27 1.27)) 
      (justify left)) 
    (uuid "a1b3def8-33c2-447c-86b3-b7388c36e919")) 
  (text "Note 1. All \"*External ...\" blocks are parts of the Vape schematic\nthat do not appear on the Vape PCB, but on another PCB within the \nVape." 
    (exclude_from_sim no) 
    (at 177.292 161.798 0) 
    (effects 
      (font 
        (size 1.27 1.27)) 
      (justify left)) 
    (uuid "a3fb05d1-6cd9-4a1c-831f-6f47fb5dc60c")) 
